{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30357,"record_hash":"sha256:96e6919e7f18aac03cce680c172948a98b0aa31db5f269b98400fd21b71289c4","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:56:56.987Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Not really a product question, more an implementation invariant.\n\nThe invariant is:\n\n```text\nmaterializing refs/meta/agentlog must only affect agentlog-scoped keys\n```\n\nSo if the remote agentlog ref contains:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-sessions\ngitbutler:agent-session:abc:transcript\n```\n\nthen materialization may update those keys locally.\n\nBut it must not touch unrelated local metadata like:\n\n```text\nreview:status\nowner:team\ngitbutler:some-future-feature\n```\n\neven though those keys are absent from the agentlog ref.\n\nThis matters because a scoped ref is necessarily partial. Absence in that ref means “not part of this key scope,” not “delete this unrelated key.”\n\nSo the thing to build/test in GitMeta is scoped materialization: it should interpret the incoming tree against the declared key matcher and only reconcile that scope. No open question from me unless you want broader behavior.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:56:56.987Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}